1459","1457":"1457","September 1, 1459":"1 September 1459","7 October 1503":"7 October 1503","1385":"1385","7 May 1457":"7 May 1457","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","Prestwood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Prestwood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Kinver, Staffordshire, England":"Kinver, Staffordshire, England","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Prestwood, Staffordshire, England":"Prestwood, Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud DePrestwood was born in 1409, in Prestwood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Nicholas Leveson. She died in 1509, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1409–1509":"1409–1509","1385–1459":"1385–1459","1457–1503":"1457–150